      <h1 class="text-3xl md:text-4xl font-bold mb-2">Health Data Consent</h1>
      <p class="text-sm text-[var(--color-text-muted)] mb-10">Version {DOC_VERSION} · Last updated: {DOC_LAST_UPDATED}</p>

      <div class="prose prose-invert max-w-none
        prose-headings:font-bold prose-headings:text-[var(--color-text)]
        prose-h2:text-xl prose-h2:mt-10 prose-h2:mb-4
        prose-h3:text-base prose-h3:mt-8 prose-h3:mb-3
        prose-p:text-[var(--color-text-muted)] prose-p:leading-relaxed
        prose-li:text-[var(--color-text-muted)]
        prose-strong:text-[var(--color-text)]
        prose-a:text-[var(--color-accent)]
        prose-ol:text-[var(--color-text-muted)]
      ">
        <h2>What this document is</h2>
        <p>This is the document you read before granting your <strong>explicit consent to process your health data</strong> so that PoopCheck can give you wellness feedback. It is <strong>not</strong> the <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice</a> (that document describes everything we do with your data). It is <strong>not</strong> the <a href="/terms/">Terms of Service</a> (that document is the contract for using the Service).</p>
        <p>Under European data-protection law (GDPR Article 9), Washington's My Health My Data Act, California's Privacy Rights Act, Quebec's Law 25, and several other privacy laws, <strong>health data</strong> is treated more strictly than ordinary personal data. The law requires that, before we process your health data, we ask for your <strong>separate, explicit, informed, freely-given consent</strong>. That is what this document is for.</p>
        <p>You can refuse this consent and you should never feel pressured to grant it. <strong>If you refuse it, the PoopCheck Service cannot work for you</strong> — we cannot analyse your stool images or your symptoms without your permission, and the core wellness feedback is what the Service does. We are honest about this trade-off because the law requires us to be, and because it is the right thing to do.</p>
        <p>If you have already granted this consent and want to withdraw it, you can do that at any time from <strong>Settings → Privacy → My consents</strong> in the app. Withdrawal is as easy as granting consent.</p>

        <h2>What we mean by "health data"</h2>
        <p>In PoopCheck, <strong>health data</strong> means everything in the list below. We treat all of it as special-category data under GDPR Art. 9 and consumer health data under Washington's My Health My Data Act:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Your stool image.</strong> The photograph you capture when you log a scan.</li>
          <li><strong>Your body metrics.</strong> Height and weight as you tell us during onboarding.</li>
          <li><strong>Your lifestyle &amp; health context.</strong> Diet pattern, hydration, sleep, stress level, coffee/alcohol intake, and any known digestive sensitivity you tell us about (for example, IBS, lactose intolerance, or celiac disease).</li>
          <li><strong>Your per-scan symptoms.</strong> Smell, pain, duration, frequency, food groups, water intake at the time, last meal, stress at the time, toilet time, and caffeine, as you choose to record them with each scan.</li>
          <li><strong>The AI's analysis of your scan.</strong> The Bristol type prediction, colour, consistency, shape, mucus, blood, quantity, narrative analysis, and action recommendations that the Service generates from your image and your answers.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Inferences we might draw from any combination of these are also health data. Washington's My Health My Data Act in particular defines "consumer health data" very broadly, and we apply that broad standard everywhere — not only to Washington consumers.</p>

        <h2>What you are consenting to with this document</h2>
        <p>This consent covers how PoopCheck processes your health data to run and improve the Service. <strong>Accepting it is required to use the app.</strong> Concretely, it means:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>uploading your image and your answers to our backend so the AI engine can analyse them;</li>
          <li>generating wellness feedback and saving it to your scan history so you can see results over time;</li>
          <li>storing your lifestyle answers on your account so we don't ask you the same questions every scan;</li>
          <li>keeping your scan history while your account is active so the timeline, charts, and trends features can work;</li>
          <li>enabling related features that need health context to work — for example, the chat feature where you can ask follow-up questions about your scan;</li>
          <li>using your data to <strong>train and improve PoopCheck's own AI models</strong> so scans get more accurate over time;</li>
          <li>generating <strong>aggregate statistics</strong> in which you are not individually identifiable, and licensing <strong>de-identified row-level datasets</strong> derived from your images and metadata to approved research buyers under contract; and</li>
          <li>processing the data for security, reliability, and legal-compliance purposes that go alongside operating the Service.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Because these uses are how PoopCheck works, <strong>if you do not accept this consent — or you later withdraw it — the Service cannot analyse your scans and the app will not function for you.</strong></p>
        <p>This consent <strong>does not</strong> cover the following two uses. Each is <strong>separate and optional</strong>: you can grant or refuse it independently, and refusing it does not affect your ability to use the app:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>licensing <strong>raw images and linked metadata</strong> to specifically named third-party buyers (separate consent: "Commercial raw-image licensing", plus a buyer-specific authorization that is signed and dated for Washington consumers under MHMDA); and</li>
          <li>sending you <strong>marketing communications</strong> (separate consent: "Marketing communications").</li>
        </ul>
        <p>You can grant or refuse those two independently, and you can change your mind at any time in <strong>Settings → Privacy</strong>.</p>

        <h2>Who processes your health data</h2>
        <p>PoopCheck (Soft All Things LLC, Wyoming, USA) is the <strong>controller</strong> of your health data — the party that decides why and how it is processed. Where the law in your country uses a different term ("business" under CPRA; "data fiduciary" under various US state laws), we play the equivalent role.</p>
        <p>To deliver the Service, we use a small number of sub-processors. They process your data on our behalf, under contracts that prohibit them from using it for their own purposes:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Google (Firebase)</strong> — authentication, document database, file storage, cloud functions, push messaging, product analytics, crash diagnostics. Multi-region (default: United States).</li>
          <li><strong>Amazon Web Services</strong> — backend hosting and S3 image storage (bucket <code>poops-softai</code>). United States.</li>
          <li><strong>RevenueCat</strong> — subscription state management (sees subscription IDs only, never your health data).</li>
          <li><strong>Apple</strong> — Apple Sign-In identity and APNs push transport (sees authentication tokens only, never your health data).</li>
          <li><strong>Google (Sign-In, FCM)</strong> — Google Sign-In identity and FCM push transport (sees authentication tokens and the push token only, never your health data).</li>
        </ul>
        <p>We do not currently use any other sub-processor.</p>

        <h2>Where your health data lives, and how it gets there safely</h2>
        <p>When you log a scan from inside the app, your image and your answers are sent over an encrypted HTTPS connection from your device to our backend. The image is stored encrypted at rest in Amazon Web Services S3 (bucket <code>poops-softai</code>, hosted in the <strong>United States</strong>). Your scan record (symptoms, AI analysis, history) is stored in Google's Firebase (Firestore + Storage). All copies of your data are encrypted at rest by the provider's default key-management service.</p>
        <p>We strip EXIF and GPS metadata from your image during upload so the image we store does not contain the location it was taken.</p>
        <p><strong>If you are in the European Economic Area, the United Kingdom, Switzerland, or Canada</strong>, your health data is transferred to the United States. That is a cross-border transfer that the law treats with extra care. We rely on EU Standard Contractual Clauses (Module 2) and the UK International Data Transfer Addendum with our US-hosted sub-processors, plus a written Transfer Impact Assessment and supplementary technical measures (encryption, access controls, audit logging, short-lived presigned URLs). The <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice</a> describes these safeguards in more detail; you can request a copy of the contractual safeguards (with confidential commercial terms redacted) by emailing the privacy contact below.</p>

        <h2>How long we keep your health data</h2>
        <ul>
          <li>While your PoopCheck account is open, we keep your scans, symptoms, and lifestyle answers so that the history, trends, and Service features can work.</li>
          <li>If you close your PoopCheck account, we delete your scans, symptoms, lifestyle answers, and AI analysis within <strong>30 days</strong> of account closure. We cascade the deletion across Firebase, our backend, AWS S3, and RevenueCat.</li>
          <li>If you only want to <strong>withdraw this consent</strong> (without closing your account), the Service can no longer function for you — we cannot do the core wellness analysis without your health data. You will be invited at that point to either close your account fully (and have everything deleted) or to place your account in a <strong>restricted</strong> state where we stop processing but retain your data temporarily so you can re-grant consent later if you change your mind.</li>
          <li>We keep a <strong>record of your consent</strong> — the fact, timestamp, document version, and method by which you granted or withdrew it — for up to <strong>7 years</strong> after the consent ends. We keep this record in pseudonymous form, because the law requires us to be able to prove the consent existed. We do not keep your health data itself; only the fact of the consent.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice's Section 9</a> has the full retention schedule for every other category of data.</p>

        <h2>Your rights</h2>
        <p>You have the following rights at any time, free of charge, under one or more of the laws that apply to you:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Withdraw this consent</strong> at any time from <strong>Settings → Privacy → My consents</strong>. Withdrawal is as easy as granting consent. We honour it within 5 seconds inside the app and within 30 days across our backend systems.</li>
          <li><strong>Access</strong> — request a copy of your health data. We provide a JSON export from <strong>Settings → Privacy → Download my data</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong>Correct</strong> — correct anything that is inaccurate.</li>
          <li><strong>Delete</strong> — have your health data permanently deleted, either through full account deletion or, for Washington consumers, through the dedicated MHMDA deletion path in <strong>Settings → Privacy → My Health My Data rights</strong>.</li>
          <li><strong>Restrict</strong> — pause processing without deleting (we hold the data, but stop using it).</li>
          <li><strong>Human review of automated AI output</strong> — if you believe an AI result is wrong, email us at <a href="mailto:poopcheck@softallthings.com">poopcheck@softallthings.com</a> and a person on our team will review it.</li>
          <li><strong>Lodge a complaint</strong> with your local data-protection regulator. The <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice</a> lists contact details for the regulators in major jurisdictions.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Where to find the rest of the picture</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong><a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice</a></strong> — describes everything we do with your data.</li>
          <li><strong>Commercial Data Use Notice</strong> — describes the three commercial programs (Tier 1 aggregate, Tier 2 de-identified, Tier 3 raw image) and how each works.</li>
          <li><strong>Third-Party Sharing / Buyer Authorization Disclosure</strong> — names the current buyer classes and recipients under the commercial programs.</li>
          <li><strong><a href="/terms/">Terms of Service</a></strong> — the contract that governs your use of the Service.</li>
          <li><strong>Settings → Privacy</strong> in the app — the place where you grant, refuse, withdraw, or change any consent at any time, and where you can download or delete your data.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>Special note for Washington consumers (MHMDA)</h2>
        <p>If you are a consumer in Washington State, the Washington <strong>My Health My Data Act</strong> applies to the health data described above. Under MHMDA:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>the definition of "consumer health data" is <strong>very broad</strong> — we apply it generously and treat every category in the list above as MHMDA-covered;</li>
          <li>we do <strong>not "sell" your consumer health data</strong> without a <strong>separate, signed, and dated authorization</strong> that names the buyer and is valid for no more than one year. That authorization is requested on a dedicated screen and is <strong>not</strong> bundled into this Health Data Consent;</li>
          <li>you have a <strong>right to know</strong>, including a list of any third parties to whom we have shared your consumer health data;</li>
          <li>you have a <strong>right to deletion</strong> that cascades across our records and our sub-processors;</li>
          <li>you have a <strong>private right of action</strong> for MHMDA violations. You can also complain to the Washington State Attorney General at <a href="https://www.atg.wa.gov" rel="noopener">atg.wa.gov</a>.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>The dedicated <strong>My Health My Data rights</strong> page in <strong>Settings → Privacy</strong> in the app explains how to exercise each of these rights.</p>

        <h2>The consent statement</h2>
        <p>By ticking the consent box at the consent gate (or, if you are reviewing this document later, by leaving the consent toggled on in <strong>Settings → Privacy → My consents</strong>), you confirm that:</p>
        <ol>
          <li>you have read this Health Data Consent document and the linked <a href="/privacy/">Privacy Notice</a>, or you have chosen not to read them in full and accept the consequences of that choice;</li>
          <li>you give your <strong>explicit, informed, and unambiguous consent</strong> under GDPR Article 9(2)(a) and the equivalent provisions of the other privacy laws that apply to you for PoopCheck (Soft All Things LLC) to process the health data described above to provide and improve the Service — including analysing and storing your scans, training PoopCheck's own AI, and producing and licensing de-identified aggregate insights and datasets for research;</li>
          <li>you understand that <strong>accepting this consent is required to use the app</strong>, and that <strong>raw-image licensing and marketing are separate, optional consents</strong> that are not required and that you can grant or refuse independently; and</li>
          <li>you understand that <strong>you can withdraw this consent at any time</strong> in <strong>Settings → Privacy → My consents</strong>, and that doing so will stop PoopCheck from processing your health data going forward but will, as a practical consequence, mean the Service can no longer provide wellness feedback for you.</li>
        </ol>
        <p>If you do not agree with any of these points, please do not tick the consent box, and please do not use the PoopCheck Service.</p>

        <h2>How to contact us</h2>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>General support and any questions about this document:</strong> <a href="mailto:poopcheck@softallthings.com">poopcheck@softallthings.com</a></li>
          <li><strong>Privacy and data-protection enquiries:</strong> <a href="mailto:dpo@poopcheck.app">dpo@poopcheck.app</a> (to be set up; in the meantime <a href="mailto:poopcheck@softallthings.com">poopcheck@softallthings.com</a> is routed to the privacy contact)</li>
          <li><strong>EU representative under GDPR Art. 27:</strong> to be appointed.</li>
          <li><strong>Quebec "Person in Charge of the Protection of Personal Information" under Law 25:</strong> to be designated.</li>
          <li><strong>Registered office:</strong> Soft All Things LLC, Wyoming, USA. Postal address available on request.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
